         <div type="entry">
                <head>Methodius, Apocalypse of Pseudo-</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Methodius-Apocalypse-of-Pseudo-</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/381</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">372</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="287"/>
                    <idno type="althead" subtype="altorder">Apocalypse of Pseudo- Methodius</idno>
                    <note type="type">work</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Influential apocalyptic work of the late 7th <abbr>cent.</abbr> 
                  <note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Influential <choice>
                            <sic>Apocalyptic</sic>
                            <corr>apocalyptic</corr>
                        </choice> work of the late 7th <abbr>cent.</abbr> Composed in Syriac and
                        ascribed to <abbr>
                            <choice>
                                <sic>bp.</sic>
                                <corr>Bp.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr> Methodius of Olympus (martyred in 312), this apocalyptic
                        survey of world history was clearly composed in the late 7th <abbr>cent.</abbr>, in
                        response to the rise of Islam. Formerly dated to earlier in the 7th <abbr>cent.</abbr>,
                        it is now thought to date from about 692, during the reign of ʿAbd al-Malik
                        (685–705). The first 7 chapters cover the period up to the rebuilding of the
                        Temple in 538 BC; beside the biblical text, these draw on traditions in the
                            <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Cave-of-Treasures">Cave of
                            Treasures</ref>. Alexander the Great is then introduced, in connection
                        with Gog and Magog, and he is linked by a remarkable genealogy to the royal
                        lineage of Ethiopia, as well as to that of Rome and Byzantium; the aim of
                        this is to explain Ps. 68:31, ‘Kush will surrender to God’, which is taken
                        to refer to the final Byzantine emperor, who will surrender his kingdom to
                        God after the appearance of the Son of Perdition (a motif borrowed from the
                            <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Julian-Romance">Julian Romance</ref>). The Apocalypse was soon translated into Greek
                        and then into Latin, where it proved very influential, especially in the
                        Medieval West. The earliest forms of the Greek and Latin are re-edited by W.
                        J. Aerts and G. A. A. Kortekaas (<abbr>CSCO</abbr> 569–70; 1998). There is a related
                        fragmentary apocalyptic text associated with <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Edessa">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/78">Edessa</placeName>
                        </ref> (<abbr>ed.</abbr> F. Nau,
                        in <title rend="italic">
                            <abbr>JA</abbr> 
                  </title> XI.9 [1917], 415–71).</p>
                </div>
